<DOCNO> AP881022-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a national institutes of health advisory 
committee says it is acceptable to use the tissue from 
intentionally aborted fetuses in medical research 
however the panels 133 vote making that fundamental finding 
the core question it was asked to decide carefully avoided taking 
a position on the morality of abortion itself or for that matter 
the morality of using the remains of planned abortions for research 
it is of moral relevance that human fetal tissue for research 
has been obtained from induced abortions said the draft document 
completed friday however in light of the fact that abortion is 
legal and that the research in question is intended to achieve 
significant medical goals the panel concludes that the use of such 
tissue is acceptable public policy 
it went on to say that the committee position must not obscure 
the profound moral dimensions of the issue of abortion nor the 
principled positions that divide scholars scientists and the 
public at large it is not the charge of this panel to attempt to 
settle the issue of abortion or to weigh the worthiness of 
competing principled perspectives on abortion itself 
researchers are hopeful that transplanting fetal brain cells 
into the brains of people with diabetes and parkinsons disease 
could provide an effective treatment perhaps in three to five 
years and that more study could lead to similar treatments for a 
number of other serious diseases for which there now is no cure 
the new procedure has been used experimentally on a handful of 
patients in other countries with promising results the advisory 
committee was formed to examine moral ethical legal and 
scientific issues after nih scientists sought permission to 
transplant fetal brain cells into some parkinsons sufferers 
the committees agreement on a lengthy draft document friday 
will not become final before nov 30 the date for submission of 
mail ballots on whether to adopt the exact language that will be 
written by nih employees working to polish the principles adopted 
by the panel over five days of discussion going back to last month 
in the draft version approved friday the panel laid out a 
number of recommended safeguards once research proceeds 
the decision to terminate a pregnancy and the procedures of 
abortion should be kept independent from the retrieval and use of 
fetal tissue 
proper and informed consent should be obtained from the 
pregnant woman 
payments and other forms of remuneration and compensation 
associated with the procurement of fetal tissue should be 
prohibited except payment for reasonable expenses occasioned by 
the actual retrieval storage preparation and transportation of 
the tissues 
potential recipients of such tissues as well as any and all 
other participants including researchers hospital personnel and 
other serviceproviders should be properly informed as to the 
source of the tissues in question 
the panel also concluded that donations of fetal tissue to a 
family member or acquaintance for medical purposes should be banned 
to discourage women from becoming pregnant with the intention of 
having an abortion and donating the tissue to a sick relative or 
close friend 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

