<TEXT>
a bill reforming the way the federal emergency 
management agency distributes aid after natural disasters has been 
approved by congress and sent to president reagan for his signature 
the disaster relief and emergency assistance amendments of 1988 
had their roots in the governments response to tornadoes that 
raced through pennsylvania ohio and new york before hitting canada 
on may 31 1985 killing 90 people 
rep thomas ridge rpa authored the bill after complaining 
that the help offered by fema in 1985 failed to meet the needs of 
residents and municipalities facing major repairs 
at a hearing on the bill last year rep leon panetta dcalif 
said reform was necessary because fema has gained the notoriety 
of being very cumbersome and tortuous for the citizens of this 
nation to understand 
the bill died in the 99th congress was introduced again last 
year and the house finally passed it in the spring 
the senate passed a companion bill by voice vote friday since 
the measure was slightly different from the version the house had 
passed earlier it was sent back to the house which approved it 
friday night 
the legislation was sent to reagan who was expected to sign it 
among other reforms the bill would bar fema from paying less 
than a 75 percent share of aid to local governments qualifying for 
public repair projects following a disaster it would add 
guidelines to speed the distribution of postdisaster aid and would 
permit federal funds to be used for the first time for local 
projects designed to lessen the effect of disasters before they 
strike 
the measure also would make temporary housing assistance through 
fema available for up to 18 months six months longer than under 
the current system 
originally the measure was opposed by the reagan 
administration which said its initial price tag 15 to 20 
million per year above what fema pays now was too high 
but the bills cost was trimmed down to zero by eliminating some 
administrative expenses and by asking state and local governments 
to share some of the cost of aid in a federally declared emergency 
among other changes 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

