<TEXT>
congress today sent president reagan a 
farreaching antidrug bill that one senate leader calls bad news 
for drug dealers and their customers 
final passage was delayed until the early morning hours as 
conservatives privately demanded antiobscenity language that was 
considered unconstitutional by many liberals and moderates 
but after negotiators compromised with language to create a new 
obscenity trafficking offense the house approved the bill 34611 
and the senate followed suit by voice vote the house vote came at 
120 am edt and the senate acted at 315 am edt 
the bill contains stiff penalties for drug traffickers and 
users and comes just in time for incumbents to trumpet its passage 
in their reelection campaigns 
senate minority leader bob dole rkan said the bill is bad 
news for drug dealers and their customers and promised that 
congress would pass even tougher medicine next year 
this is a very strong bill said senate majority leader 
robert byrd dwva the message is simple dont do drugs the 
country will not tolerate it 
the bill would fight illegal drugs through law enforcement 
stiffer penalties treatment rehabilitation education and aid for 
authorities in drugproducing countries 
the compromise legislation a product of marathon senatehouse 
negotiations this week would send a strong message that even 
recreational drug use is unacceptable 
the bill would make it possible for those possessing small 
quantities of drugs intended for personal use to be hit with up to 
10000 in civil fines with the right of court review beginning 
next september those convicted of drug offenses including 
possession could face loss of student loans and other federal 
benefits for even a possession conviction 
drug kingpins and others who kill or order killings while 
committing drugrelated felonies could themselves be executed under 
a revitalized federal death penalty serious drug offenses would 
carry stiffer minimum prison terms 
language to strengthen the federal obscenity law was included in 
the compromise by congressional leaders seeking to avoid a 
threatened conservative revolt at all costs leaders have insisted 
the bill be acceptable to republicans and democrats liberals and 
conservatives 
negotiators were unable to resolve disputes and thus left out 
of the final bill proposals for random drug testing for 
transportation workers and those with safetyrelated jobs at 
nuclear facilities 
the legislation provides about 500 million in new spending 
which would barely cover a third of the firstyear cost of an 
estimated 14 billion 
the ineligibility for benefits could affect public housing 
grants contracts loans mortgage guarantees and some forms of 
veterans aid but not social security medicare welfare benefits 
veterans disability and other safetynet programs judges would 
have discretion in imposing the penalties after a conviction 
the president would submit a report to congress on the program 
next may allowing lawmakers to reconsider the proposal before the 
scheduled september 1989 start of the punishment 
the capital punishment provision provides that if someone is 
killed during a federal drug felony the death penalty could apply 
if the killer was engaged in a continuing criminal enterprise was 
trafficking in major amounts of cocaine heroin or other drugs 
intentionally gave an order that resulted in a killing or killed a 
police officer 
to coordinate the nations antidrug policy a drug czar 
would be added to the presidents cabinet the official would 
develop plans for every phase of the drug war share with relevant 
cabinet members the authority to transfer personnel and have the 
right to object when he believes drug funding is inadequate or 
misdirected 
the obscenity trafficking section would allow the government to 
prosecute those engaged in the business of obscenity who derive 
income from their dealings in obscene materials 
the traffickers could be forced to forfeit the obscene material 
and their profits other property belonging to them could be seized 
at a judges discretion 
</TEXT>
