<TEXT>
a new allegation of alcohol abuse at a nuclear 
power plant illustrates the need for strict federal regulations to 
detect substance abuse at atomic reactors says the chairman of a 
house investigations subcommittee 
it is the nuclear regulatory commissions responsibility to 
protect against drug and alcohol abuse said rep sam gejdenson 
dconn chairman of the house interior and insular affairs 
subcommittee on investigations and oversight it is not enough 
for the nrc to leave it to the industry to regulate itself 
gejdenson who has held a series of hearings on the question of 
substance abuse at nuclear plants wants the nrc to issue stiff 
regulations on drug and alcohol abuse instead of leaving 
regulations up to individual utilities 
the commission proposed a new rule last month that would require 
reactor owners to conduct random drug tests test employees for 
drugs based on cause report drug use to the nrc and mandate 
personnel sanctions but the rule would leave alcohol detection and 
enforcement up to the prudent judgment of each utility 
commission officials say no final decision has been made on the 
proposed regulation 
in latest allegation of substance abuse at an atomic reactor 
gejdenson provided the associated press with an nrc document 
outlining an accusation made by an employee at the clinton power 
station in clinton ill against a senior plant manager 
the employee according to the report told a superior that the 
manager had alcohol on his breath and stumbled as he passed through 
a radiationdetecting device on the night of oct 10 
but officials at illinois power co operator of the reactor 
said the company hired a private investigator the next day who 
concluded several days later that there was no evidence of alcohol 
abuse 
stephen perry assistant vice president at the plant defended 
the utilitys internal substance abuse program 
in a telephone interview friday perry said the employee who 
was charged with checking for fires at the reactor reported his 
accusation to a superior the shift supervisor talked to the senior 
manager at length and decided there was no evidence of alcohol 
perry said under the companys internal regulations the manager 
could have been ordered to take a blood test if the supervisor 
found cause he said such blood tests have been ordered in the past 
the subsequent investigation turned up no evidence to 
corroborate the alcohol charge he said 
but gejdenson who wrote a letter to nrc chairman lando w zech 
jr last week urging a strict rule on both alcohol and drugs and a 
top gejdenson aide said it is wrong to rely on selfpolicing and 
criticized the nrc for not conducting its own investigation 
at the very least you want the nrc to do is find out what 
happened said subcommittee investigator john scheibel the nrc 
cant take the trouble to send somebody out there 
the nrc is in a position of public trust and at the very 
least the public can expect the nrc to act cautiously and not just 
accept the word of the person who said no there was no 
problem he said 
commission spokesman frank ingram said the nrc was looking 
into the allegation but said he did not know to what extent 
scheibel said he was told by nrc officials the agency is not 
conducting a separate investigation 
scheibel noted that the senior manager in question was a higher 
ranking official at the company than the shift supervisor who would 
have had to order the blood test he said that could be an 
inhibiting factor 
but plant officials said a thorough and independent 
investigation was conducted and that no other employees 
corroborated the alcohol allegation 
the clinton report comes on the heels of a subcommittee hearing 
earlier this month that focused on an allegation of alcohol abuse 
against a plant manager at the davisbesse reactor near toledo 
ohio 
