last chance to stop the capital from going to the dogs 
this week they vote on an experimental program relaxing a ban 
on dogs in the city of 88000 the weeklong referendum begins 
monday and asks voters to say whether the 4yearold program has 
been a success 
city hall banished dogs in 1924 following an outbreak of 
dogrelated disease for 60 years it resisted attempts to overturn 
the ban despite ridicule from abroad and lurid stories about mass 
slaughter of illicit dogs 
in 1978 dog owners went to the supreme court in an unsuccessful 
bid to have the ban declared unconstitutional the issue made 
headlines again when albert gudmundsson then the finance minister 
threatened to emigrate unless he could keep his dog in reykjavik 
compromise finally came in 1984 when city hall while keeping 
the ban on the books set up some exemptions and promised a 
referendum after four years on how reykavik and mans best friend 
were getting along 
we are of the opinion that the vote is not necessary because 
of the good experience weve had in allowing conditional 
dogownership mayor david oddsson who owns a german shepherd 
named tanni fang recently told morgunbladid icelands main 
newspaper 
but nevertheless the promised ballot box is being set up in the 
city sports hall and citizens will vote yes or no on the question 
do you think that the experimental dog rules have been 
successful 
oddsson said the vote is not binding but if there is an 
overwhelming majority either way then we must take notice of 
that 
with opinion polls showing 21 support for the exemptions dog 
owners are confident 
but one city official magnus oskarsson said voters are so 
apathetic on the issue they may ignore the referendum and give 
antidog forces a victory by default 
strict rules apply to reykjaviks 850 registered dog owners 
annual licenses cost 120 dogs must undergo an annual medical 
checkup and owners must have insurance 
the city center is permanently out of bounds and dogs must stay 
out of public parks between 8 am and 9 pm they cannot enter 
public buildings restaurants childrens playgrounds barbershops 
prisons cemeteries morgues and buses leashes are always required 
according to city veterinarian oddur runar hjartarson the ban 
was imposed after dogs began transferring a dangerous sheep disease 
to human beings 
hyatid disease which once infected an estimated 20 percent of 
icelands population is caused by a worm that can cause blindness 
in people and even death hjartarson said dogs picked up the 
disease from eating the intestines of slaughtered sheep 
the disease has since been eradicated and illegal dog ownership 
has become rampant along with the lurid stories 
there were all these stories in the foreign press about dogs 
being caught and killed it never happened i recall perhaps one 
example of a dog being impounded oskarsson said 
gudrun gudjohnsen president of the dogbreeding association 
warns a new ban would be a big step backward and not likely to 
be enforced 
during the 60 years of the old ban there were hundreds of 
dogs in the capital people ought to realize that it is far 
better to have an effective monitoring and control system than 
going back to a system of no control she said 
</TEXT>
