<TEXT>
the difficulty of reaching a shortterm 
agreement under which the united states keeps its military bases in 
the philippines raises what was once an unthinkable notion an 
eventual american pullout from subic bay navy base and clark air 
base 
the agreement signed last week after six months of 
sometimesbitter negotiations covers only the use of the bases 
until 1991 providing for 962 million in economic and military aid 
for the philippines over the next two years it is a sharp 
increase but many filipino politicians say its far from enough 
if the americans are to remain beyond sept 30 1991 the 
negotiators probably will face difficulties which were only hinted 
at in this years talks according to analysts 
fred brown a southeast asia scholar said until the talks 
brought to the fore the spectre of a us pullout from the 
philippines it was sort of an unthinkable unmentionable 
issue as the talks were going on both secretary of state george 
shultz and defense secretary frank carlucci said the united states 
could move its bases if the philippines demanded too much 
brown who is with the carnegie endowment for international 
peace an independently funded think tank predicted that if 
nationalist forces continue to shape the debate in the philippines 
over the bases negotiators for both sides will consider a phaseout 
of the us presence in the philippines 
the debate in the philippines also will be affected by how well 
the current agreement is implemented 
the funds promised in the agreement while falling short of the 
annual 12 billion sought by the philippines are still 
substantially higher than the us aid appropriated by congress in 
previous years for use of the bases and in light of the us 
budget crunch the difference is significant 
sen bob dole leader of the republican minority in the senate 
raised a warning flag just how that money is going to be found 
in a foreign operations budget already carved to the bone to meet 
other base rights and peacekeeping commitments is not readily 
apparent to this senator 
but an influential legislative aide who spoke only on condition 
of anonymity said that there is enough bipartisan support for the 
philippines so that there are ways the money could be found he 
conceded this would mean shortchanging other aid recipients or 
wrangling with the defense department for some of its money it 
wont be easy he said 
another struggle is expected over a us contribution to a 5 
billion multinational aid program to help ease the philippines 28 
billion debt although the package is unrelated resolution of the 
base pact was expected to boost support in congress for the 
international initiative 
the united states is spearheading the effort although japan 
will foot most of the bill 
the international aid package if it is approved and funded 
will grant legitimacy to the usphilippine bases agreement in 
the eyes of the filipino public and leadership said john bresnan 
a senior research associate at the school of east asia of columbia 
university 
so far president corazon aquino is facing a hard time selling 
