<TEXT>
the lebanese with rival moslem and 
christian groups claiming to govern them fear the monthlong 
turmoil over a new president will formally sever ties that kept the 
nation together through a 13year civil war 
we have no president and parliament is lost what is there to 
help lebanon survive said kazem khalil 88 the eldest of 
lebanons parliamentary deputies and an architect of the countrys 
independence from france in 1943 
this is the worst crisis weve ever had said khalil 
appointed interim parliament speaker last week the political 
social and economic systems have ceased to exist we just dont 
know where were heading 
he echoed the despair of most lebanese at the creeping partition 
of the country into moslem and christian cantons after parliament 
failed to elect a president to succeed amin gemayel when his 
sixyear term expired sept 23 
parliamentary efforts failed because christian deputies opposed 
to syrianbacked candidates who were the most serious contenders 
boycotted the electoral sessions and blocked a quorum 
gemayel appointed army commander gen michel aoun a maronite 
catholic head of a caretaker military government minutes before he 
stepped down 
but acting prime minister salim hoss a sunni moslem declared 
that his cabinet installed under gemayel was the legitimate one 
three moslem army officers named as ministers under aoun quit 
all but one christian in hoss cabinet resigned and handed their 
ministries over to aoun 
the crisis deepened last week when parliament failed to elect a 
new speaker to succeed hussein husseini a prosyrian shiite 
moslem after his oneyear term expired khalil was appointed in 
the session which once again was boycotted by the christians 
the americans had sought with the syrians to produce a 
compromise candidate for the presidency but have backed off 
diplomatic efforts until after the us presidential election nov 
8 one wellinformed lebanese said 
the united states now appears to be as much at a loss about 
lebanese as the leaders of lebanon themselves said the source 
who spoke on condition of anonymity 
despite widespread fears that the constitutional crisis will 
touch off new fighting there have been only sporadic clashes 
between christians and moslems 
the two sides after years of warfare and intervention by syria 
iraq israel and libya have achieved a military balance 
the estimated 800000 christians led by samir geagea a former 
medical student who commands their main militia have been 
receiving shiploads of weapons and ammunition from iraq 
baghdad freed from the gulf war against iran by an aug 20 
ceasefire has been arming the christians to sabotage syrias 
efforts to pacify lebanon 
syria iraqs archrival in the arab world backed iran during 
the war and supports lebanons estimated 17 million moslems 
the christians are armed to the teeth a senior lebanese 
army officer said also speaking on condition of anonymity 
they can defend themselves against any moslem or syrian 
attack but they cant attack or make any territorial gains 
the stalemate has sent prices of food gasoline and other basics 
soaring a 22pound can of powdered milk cost 4000 lebanese 
pounds friday against 2700 pounds monday 
the lebanese pound pegged at 8 to the dollar in 1982 and 337 on 
sept 22 was at 540 friday 
so far the rival governments have not embarked on an economic 
war 
the christians easily could cut off electricity fuel and water 
supplies to moslem west beirut 
they may be refraining because the central bank where 70 
percent of lebanons 93 million ounces in gold reserves are held 
is located on the moslem side 
</TEXT>
