<TEXT>
one of the first lessons learned by a member 
of congress is that theres no better way to keep voters happy than 
to cut their taxes 
theres no money left in the federal treasury to grant any more 
acrosstheboard tax reductions such as were approved in 1981 but 
that doesnt prevent the lawmakers from granting targeted relief to 
one group after another 
thats exactly what they did in the tax bill that cleared its 
final hurdle in congress on saturday it now goes to president 
reagan and sponsors predict he will sign it 
the bill originally was designed to clear up confusing language 
and correct errors in the landmark tax overhaul enacted in 1986 
but it was amended over and over to extend some expiring benefits 
add some new ones for selected groups and raise taxes to finance 
the benefits 
the measure would have no effect on the federal deficit 
although it would cut taxes by 41 billion over three years it 
would raise others by the same amount 
and it is not just tax cuts and increases that were attached to 
the bill it includes a taxpayers bill of rights to rein in 
what some lawmakers view as an overly aggressive internal revenue 
service for example the agency would have to give 30 days notice 
before seizing bank accounts and other property and would be 
prohibited from promoting employees on the basis of how much they 
collect 
some of the other provisions 
diesel wipe out a 1987 requirement that farmers construction 
companies and other taxexempt offroad users of diesel fuel pay 
the federal tax of 151 cents a gallon and later apply for a refund 
mutual funds for 1988 and 1989 permit owners of mutual fund 
shares to deduct certain operating expenses of the fund without 
regard to a general provision allowing deduction of only 
miscellaneous expenses that exceed 2 percent of income 
higher education exempt from taxation interest earned on us 
savings bonds that are redeemed to finance a college or vocational 
education starting in 1990 
tuition aid renew for 1988 an expired law allowing a worker to 
avoid tax on up to 5250 a year of employerprovided education 
assistance graduate education would not qualify 
housing extend through 1989 a tax credit for owners of newly 
constructed lowincome rental housing also extend through 1989 
and modify a tax exemption for bonds issued by state and local 
governments to help lowincome families buy their first home 
tobacco impose a tax of 45 cents per pound on pipe tobacco 
writers allow freelance writers artists and photographers to 
deduct workrelated expenses even before a project produces income 
heifer tax permit livestock farmers to deduct expenses of 
producing livestock before the animals begin generating income 
thus repealing what has become known as the heifer tax 
athletics allow an 80 percent deduction for contributions to 
college athletic scholarship funds even when such gifts 
guarantee a fan the privilege of buying a game ticket 
research extend through 1989 a credit for increased spending 
for research and experimentation 
job training extend through 1989 a credit under which the 
government pays the first year of wages for certain newly hired 
economically disadvantaged workers 
contractors further restrict the completedcontract method 
of accounting that allows defense contractors and most big 
construction companies to delay taxes on part of their profits 
until a project is completed this change will raise 13 billion 
corporations accelerate estimated tax payments from 
corporations that switch from an annualized method of computation 
raising 869 million 
alaska corporations repeal a provision that has allowed alaska 
native corporations to sell some of their unused tax credits to 
other companies repeal will cost the alaska companies 1 billion 
life insurance remove some of the tax advantages of using 
singlepremium life insurance as an investment loans from such 
policies would be taxed as cash withdrawals the new rules would 
apply to policies whose cash value builds more quickly than one 
paid through seven equal annual premiums the change would cost 
policyholders 345 million 
mail carriers allow rural mail carriers to deduct 3375 cents 
for each mile a personal car is driven on a mail route most people 
are allowed 225 cents a mile for businessrelated mileage 
business meals permit operators of offshore or alaska oil rigs 
and of some commercial vessels but not luxury liners to deduct 
the full cost of meals provided to employees most business may 
deduct only 80 percent 
home sale allow a surviving spouse to defer taxation on 
profits from the sale of a principal home just as though the 
spouse had not died present law denies such a break if a spouse 
dies after a home is sold and before a new one is built also the 
provision allowing a person over 55 to avoid tax on up to 125000 
of profits from the sale of a principal home in which he or she had 
lived at least three of the last five years would be available to a 
person who spends up to four of those five years in a nursing home 
home phone prohibit any person with a homebased business from 
deducting any part of the base monthly telephone charge as a 
business expense 
farm machinery tighten depreciation provisions for 
singlepurpose farm structures such as poultry houses and farm 
machinery 
farm income expand a law allowing farmers to defer for one 
year income from the droughtforced sale of livestock also the 
measure would ensure that farmers may defer taxes on payments 
received as a result of droughtcaused crop losses 
banks renew a tax break for healthy savings and loan 
associations that take over failing associations and extend the 
benefit to banks 
highspeed rail permit use of taxexempt bonds to finance 
certain highspeed rail facilities 
blood donors permit states and bloodcollection facilities to 
require blood donors to list their social security numbers so they 
can be traced if tests determine their blood is carrying the aids 
virus 
amish exempt from social security taxes employees from amish 
and other sects with religious objections to the program 
selfemployed amish already are exempt 
</TEXT>
