<DOCNO> AP881022-0104 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
fire and flood consumed the stage of the 
metropolitan opera house in the final scene of wagners 
goetterdaemmerung but instead of fleeing in panic the 
audience leapt to its feet and cheered 
the triumphant premiere of the new production friday night meant 
that the nations leading opera house had forged the final link in 
its longawaited new production of wagners epic ring cycle 
the sets and the lighting were among the most spectacular ever 
seen at the met and at least as far as the heroine and the villain 
were concerned it seemed as if the company had even brought back 
the muchlamented bygone golden era of wagnerian singing 
soprano hildegard behrens singing and acting with passion and 
elegance as the noble bruennhilde consolidated her claim as a 
worthy successor to the great birgit nilsson she and bass matti 
salminen as the baleful hagen dominated the stage and easily 
penetrated even the cruelest waves of sound that wagner and the 
met orchestra could provide 
not for 13 seasons had the company performed this last and 
longest nearly six hours including two intermissions of the four 
operas in which wagner intertwined norse mythology and 19th century 
german philosophy with sometimes muddled but generally powerful 
results 
twilight of the gods as the opera is called in english 
turns on hagens determination to get his hands on the magical gold 
ring that has been the source of all the trouble since his father 
alberich stole it from the rhinemaidens in the first opera das 
rheingold 
the plot twists might seem silly were they not redeemed by 
wagners glorious music which carries the audience through 
contrivances like an amnesiainducing potion and a magical helmet 
that disguises siegfried so bruennhilde cant recognize her own 
husband when he kidnaps her 
the sets by guenther schneidersiemssen have combined naturalism 
with hightech effects throughout the earlier operas and reach 
their artistic peak in act 3 the first scene a forest clearing 
where hagen murders siegfried is strikingly realistic the tableau 
resembling a flemish painting gil wechslers lighting moves subtly 
from dappled sunlight to encroaching darkness as the heros doom 
approaches 
but the real stage wizardry is saved for the finale when 
bruennhildes suicide in siegfrieds funeral pyre literally sets 
the world ablaze causes the rhine to overflow and even burns up 
valhalla the kingdom of the gods all this is vividly brought to 
life as the orchestra splendidly conducted by james levine pours 
out the final measures of the score 
in a performance so strong its a shame the biggest weakness was 
the siegfried of toni kramer he seemed ill at ease on stage his 
mediumsized voice showed severe strain by act 2 and he gave only 
a workmanlike rendition of his wonderful final narrative baritone 
anthony raffell failed to make much impression in the thankless 
role of gunther hagens halfbrother soprano kathryn harries did 
better as gunthers sister gutrune but had trouble with her high 
notes 
in the small but vital role of waltraute bruennhildes sister 
mezzo christa ludwig who was singing in ring cycles 20 years ago 
made a dazzling impression and provided a valuable link with a 
tradition the met is bidding to revive 
goetterdaemmerung will be performed several more times this 
fall in the spring the met will stage three complete rings one 
of them on successive saturday afternoons in april for a nationwide 
radio audience 
</TEXT>
