<TEXT>
meat prices rose saturday and bread 
prices will rise by 60 percent the government said two days after 
an unpopular austerity program was amended to allow salary raises 
for some workers 
the belgrade daily politika ekspres said the latest price 
increases will drive the remaining shoppers out of meat markets 
and will further depress living standards 
thousands of yugoslavs in recent weeks have protested rising 
prices in a growing economic crisis in the communist nation 
as of saturday prime quality steak cost 636 a pound in 
belgrade up from 555 ground meat rose from 221 to 339 a 
pound 
the cheapest type of bread now available for 5 cents a pound 
will cost 8 cents when new bread prices take effect sunday 
politika ekspres said 
statistics published here say living standards have dropped to 
the level of the mid1960s inflation is running as high as 217 
percent 
meat prices were boosted considerably three weeks ago last 
year the government had to cancel sharp increases in bread prices 
after widespread protests 
the average monthly income in yugoslavia is 100 and experts 
say about 80 percent of it goes for food 
faced with increasing strikes and worker protests parliament on 
thursday eased an austerity program of wage cuts and price rises 
introduced in may 
the amendments allow wages increases of 140 percent to 152 
percent this year but only for workers in profitable companies and 
in hardpressed social services like health and education 
another belgrade newspaper vecernje novosti said about half of 
yugoslav companies employing more than 2 million workers will not 
be able to increase their wages because they are not making profits 
</TEXT>
