<TEXT>
hurricane joan slammed into nicaragua 
and costa rica today with 125 mph winds and blinding rain killing 
at least seven people and forcing thousands on the regions 
carribean coast to flee inland 
the hurricanes winds later dropped to 70 mph and it was 
downgraded to a tropical storm but forecasters predicted heavy 
rains from the storm would cause flash floods and mud slides in 
nicaragua costa rica and honduras 
nicaraguan radio reported three dead and dozens injured on great 
corn island about 45 miles off the city of bluefields and costa 
rican authorities said four drowned and seven were missing there 
more than 77000 people were evacuated in the two countries 
authorities said 
on nicaraguas coast the storm flattened homes felled trees 
and cut communications about 1000 people were evacuated in the 
early morning darkness after flood waters threatened to engulf a 
neighborhood in bluefields 180 miles east of managua the group 
was taken to a municipal building to ride out the storm the state 
radio voice of nicaragua reported 
precautionary evacuations also began in managua as the storm 
swept inland according to a newspaper report 
severe flooding also was reported in coastal costa rican towns 
officials there said costa rica has never been hit by a hurricane 
in recorded history and the last one that hit nicaragua was in 
1911 
earlier this week the storm left at least 26 people dead and 
tens of thousands homeless in colombia and venezuela 
forecasters with the national hurricane center in coral gables 
fla said the storm traveling west at 8 mph weakened as it 
passed over land 
joan struck great corn island late friday state radio reported 
heavy winds and rain knocked out power in rama 60 miles west of 
bluefields and strong downpours were reported in central chontales 
and southern rio san juan provinces 
flash flood and mud slide warnings were issued for costa rica 
nicaragua western panama and eastern honduras forecasters 
predicted more than 15 inches of rain would inundate those areas by 
sunday 
storm surges of 10 to 15 feet were expected near and just to the 
north of the hurricanes center 
at noon edt today joans center was near latitude 119 north 
and longitude 845 west or 120 miles east of managua maximum 
sustained winds were 70 mph 
the danger is effective and real there exists a great danger 
of loss of life in the city of bluefields information minister 
manuel espinoza said friday night 
neighborhood civil defense committees in nicaragua stacked 
sandbags to form levees against flooding 
heavy winds and rain prompted the government to evacuate 
hospitals in puerto cabezas 120 miles north of bluefields and in 
boaco an inland city 45 miles northeast of managua 
under an emergency law declared thursday the government ordered 
private firms to make available stocks of goods necessary to 
confront the hurricane 
julio aragon in juigalpa nicaragua 100 miles west of the 
caribbean coast said refugees were streaming into the city ahead 
of the storm 
theyre carrying everything they can chickens pigs sacks 
of beans and other small belongings he said 
the san juan and colorado rivers near the nicaraguan border 
spilled their banks as did the coto river on the pacific side 
officials said 
costa rican officials feared joan could destroy many of the 
20000 banana plantations along the coast 
