here is a chronology of major events in the attempts to free the 
three trapped whales in barrow alaska 
oct 13 the california gray whales were discovered trapped in 
the ice east of point barrow they apparently became stuck a week 
before biologists were unable to contact an icebreaker to give aid 
oct 14 the whales continued to swim several hundred feet 
offshore using two holes in the ice to breathe biologists 
believed time was running out for the grays as nighttime 
temperatures dropped to 13 degrees below zero threatening to 
shrink the whales breathing space efforts failed again to contact 
an icebreaking ship 
oct 18 a biologist said one whale may have pneumonia as an 
alaska army national guard skycrane helicopter went to tow a 
185ton hovercrafttype icebreaking barge 200 miles northwest to 
the whales president reagan telephoned with his support 
oct 19 eskimos cut new holes in ice but the barge effort was 
hampered by shallow water biologists said the whales health 
appeared to be stabilized and that they were handling their 
captivity better than first believed 
oct 20 the barge began its journey but moved only about six 
miles through sand bars mud and shallow water two minnesota 
brothersinlaw arrive with deicers to enlarge breathing holes for 
whales 
oct 21 one of the whales nicknamed bone disappeared and 
was presumed dead rescuers tried plan b a fiveton concrete 
bullet wielded by a helicopter loaned by the alaska army 
national guard easterly wind opened leads or open water 
through the ice within four miles of the whales the soviet union 
offered an icebreaker to help in the rescue 
oct 22 eskimos using chain saws had led the whales almost a 
halfmile closer to open water by carving a string of 24 breathing 
holes in the ice the skycrane dropping its bullet had punched 
four 15to20foot holes in the ice at 75yard intervals but a 
massive pressure ridge of ice stood in the way 
</TEXT>
