<TEXT>
a rare public rift in the jewish community 
controversy over a political memo and harsh words from defense 
secretary frank carlucci have focused attention on aipac one of 
the most powerful lobbying groups on capitol hill 
the american israel public affairs committee referred to as 
aipac is wellknown in the corridors of power even though its 
staff generally stays out of the limelight and prefers to work 
behind the scenes 
thomas a dine aipacs executive director rarely gives 
interviews and aipac officials are not regulars on the television 
and radio talk show circuit 
yet aipac has compiled a stunningly successful record since 1951 
in promoting the relationship between the united states and israel 
jerusalem is the largest recipient of us economic and military 
aid amounting to 3 billion this year 
its the strongest lobby in washington the strongest lobby in 
the country said former rep paul findley an illinois 
republican who wrote a book attacking aipac after his defeat in 
1982 
it remains a powerhouse on capitol hill because they have an 
excellent highly professional highly trained staff he said 
aipac staff members track legislation and have broad contacts at 
the state department and in the white house 
aipac and its allies in congress have played a large role in 
opposing the sale of weapons to saudi arabia jordan bahrain and 
kuwait 
carlucci in a speech to an arabamerican group friday said 
congressional opposition to the sale of weapons to moderate arab 
countries was costing the united states tens of billions of 
dollars worth of jobs 
saudi arabia upset that its attempts to buy weapons such as new 
fighter jets and maverick antitank missiles from washington often 
have been stymied by congress recently signed a deal with britain 
to buy more than 30 billion worth of weapons 
carlucci did not mention aipac by name but he criticized 
various interest groups and many in congress for trying to 
block sales to arab countries 
the notion that us defense cooperation with moderate arab 
states poses a danger to israel is illfounded and untrue he 
said 
but rep mel levine dcalif a strong backer of israel said 
such sales are not in the american interest of peace in the 
middle east 
findley in a telephone interview from jacksonville ill said 
he thinks aipacs real power stems from an indirect linkage between 
the lobby and proisrael political action committees controlled by 
jewish groups 
aipac strenuously denies the allegation and says it does not 
make political contributions or endorse candidates 
spokeswoman toby dershowitz reiterated this position in a letter 
to washington jewish week which had published a story saying the 
cbstv show 60 minutes was looking into the relationship 
between aipac and proisrael political action committees 
60 minutes has no new evidence that aipac coordinates or 
directs pacs she said adding that earlier allegations fall 
far short of proving any such direction or coordination 
dershowitz also disavowed a 1987 memo written by a former junior 
staffer at the lobbying group to another exstaffer barbara 
amouyal 
the memo discussed the senate race in rhode island describing 
republican incumbent john chafee as a poor supporter of our 
issue it called for encouragement of the candidacy of richard 
licht the states lieutenant governor who is jewish 
no such negative campaign exists against chafee dershowitz 
said 
while aipac always has been a magnet for criticism from some 
members of congress the airing of a disagreement in the jewish 
community over the lobbys activities was unusual 
six officials of the american jewish committee the american 
jewish congress and the antidefamation league of the bnai brith 
complained in a letter that aipac had taken positions that were not 
in accord with the consensus of the organized jewish community 
the complaint was in the form of a letter that appeared first in 
the new york times 
the letter said aipac erred in trying to close the palestine 
liberation organizations un office in new york and some jewish 
leaders disagreed with aipacs opposition to a big kuwaiti arms 
deal 
last week the groups tried to paper over any differences with 
aipac 
they issued a statement in which they pledged to be fully 
supportive of aipacs work the three groups were among the 
founding members of aipac in 1951 
some of israels supporters on capitol hill also played down the 
significance of any rift 
do all jews have the same opinion on israel no said rep 
barney frank dmass but that doesnt translate into an overall 
lessening of support for israel he said 
although aipac officials generally do a good job frank 
said i think they sometimes tend to overkill 
the jewish community is not homogeneous said rep larry 
smith dfla who said i dont think it is anything but healthy 
to have different points of view on issues 
but rep mervyn dymally dcalif chairman of the congressional 
black caucus and an aipac critic said the open disagreement could 
weaken the lobby because when leaders begin to speak out then 
aipac will moderate their views 
aipacs money comes from its 50000 members who sent 
contributions the group which has a staff of about 70 will 
operate with a budget of 66 million this year dershowitz said 
six people registered as lobbyists for aipac between april and 
july this year lobbying reports filed with the senate show that 
dine and aipacs chief lobbyist douglas bloomfield each earned 
about 21000 in the second quarter of 1988 
meantime former cia agent victor marchetti and author mark lane 
said they have asked the justice department to investigate whether 
aipac should be registered as a lobby for a foreign government 
under the 1938 foreign agents registration act 
department spokesman john russell said the agency determined in 
the 1970s that aipac was not required to register because none of 
its money came from israel 
