<DOCNO> AP881022-0180 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
one year after black monday the question of which government 
agency should oversee the financial futures markets remains 
unresolved a fact highlighted this past week at a gathering of 
futures industry leaders and regulators in chicago 
a number of other crashrelated issues also overhang the 
nations futures and options exchanges but none arouses a more 
emotional response among futures industry leaders than the control 
question especially among officials of the chicago mercantile 
exchange and the chicago board of trade the worlds largest 
futures exchanges 
futures and options trading is regulated by the 14yearold 
commodities and futures trading commission trading of stocks and 
bonds is regulated by the securities and exchange commission set 
up in 1934 as part of the new deal 
despite the undeniable link between the stock market and 
stockindex futures which can be used for either hedging stock 
positions or speculating on stockmarket movements the chicago 
exchanges have strongly opposed postcrash proposals that one 
agency should regulate both markets 
instead they have argued for the creation of an agency that 
would coordinate sharing of trading information among all the 
financial markets 
sec chairman david ruder asked congress in january to enlarge 
his agencys jurisdiction to give it direct regulatory 
authority over stockindex futures and any new futures contracts 
related to stocks 
in chicago on thursday ruder took a more lenient stance saying 
postcrash efforts to better coordinate the activities of the sec 
the cftc and the markets were working satisfactorily 
nonetheless ruder said in a speech to the economic club of 
chicago i continue to believe that in the long term there needs 
to be an ability to look beyond the parochial concerns of each of 
the separate stock and futures markets in the long run unified 
jurisdiction over these increasingly linked and unified markets 
will prove to be desirable 
earlier in the day while sitting on a discussion panel with 
cftc chairwoman wendy gramm and four futures industry leaders 
ruder was even more conciliatory on the issue saying that 
contrary to many press reports i do not regard that as a very 
serious matter 
chicago merc president william brodsky who also sat on the 
panel expressed his position bluntly i dont think you need a 
single regulator to create cooperation 
ms gramm a reagan appointee who has been in office less than 
eight months did not comment on the control issue but focused 
instead on the likelihood of increased regulation of futures 
trading under a michael dukakis administration 
dukakis is a democrat and most of the bills introduced in 
congress in the past year proposing greater regulation of the 
futures markets were sponsored by democrats 
but ms gramm said she expected republican vice president george 
bush to win the november election the big question she said was 
whether bush would be willing to veto any futuresrelated 
legislation backed by a congress likely to be dominated by 
democrats 
the issue of regulatory jurisdiction over financial futures 
could come to a head next year when congress must vote on 
reauthorizing the cftc for another four years by law the agency 
dies next year unless reauthorized by congress 
