<TEXT>
chevron usa citing increased 
competition and reduced profit announced plans friday to cut the 
workforce at its largest refinery by about 400 jobs 
company officials said a portion of the jobs will be eliminated 
through attrition and early retirement 
the 4000acre plant was purchased by the chevron subsidiary in 
1984 from gulf oil corp and employs more than 2200 people 
chevron usa has announced plans to streamline the refinery 
operations and the organization here to make the refinery more 
competitive and not only to make it more competitive but to 
assure its continued operation said company spokesman art 
spencer 
the exact number of layoffs will not be known until company 
officials meet with union leaders to discuss the changes he said 
but chevron plans to operate the plant with about 400 fewer 
employees 
any announcement involving a reduction in manpower is 
difficult but this has come as something of a relief to many of 
our port arthur business people because it means that chevron has 
decided to keep the plant open spencer said 
a company task force had presented four options to improve 
refining operation profits including the possibility of shutting 
down the plant or reducing the workforce by more than half 
spencer sasid 
this was the best of the task force alternatives he said 
its a relief that we did not have to go to the big numbers 
the changes were prompted in part by continuing volatility in 
the energy industry he said 
it relates to the extremely competitive market in which this 
refinery functions spencer said 
this gulf coast region is the most competitive petroleum 
products market in the united states he said we have not been 
competitive in this market for a long time 
smaller chevron refining operations in pascagoula miss and el 
paso have proven more profitable he said 
the port arthur refinery is the largest owned by chevron with 
an operating capacity off 407000 barrels of crude per day after 
streamlining which is expected to begin immediately ready 
capacity will be about 329000 barrels per day spencer said 
weve never run 400000 barrels a day here he said 
a renewed marketing strategy calls for the refinery to place a 
greater emphasis on the production of petrochemicals premium 
unleaded gasoline and lubricating base oils spencer said the 
plant is one of few along the gulf coast with its own packaging 
facilities 
the company plans to complete the cutbacks by the end of the 
first quarter 1989 spencer said 
the port arthur refinery first opened in 1901 and has undergone 
numerous renovations including a 600million improvement project 
in 1980 he said 
</TEXT>
